 Thetis and the Nereids as Patrons of Ancient Greek Mariners -- tPart IV: Reception – Thetis’ Aftermaths -- tThe Wicked Witch of the West? Thetis’ Controversial Transformations in 14th- Century Middle English Vernacular Poetry -- tReading Thetis in Tirso de Molina’s El Aquiles -- tThetis and the Shield of Achilles — Reading the Iliad with Auden -- tThetis of the Silver Screen: The Vengeful and Cosmic Goddess in Clash of the Titans -- tSea Witches in Exile: Thetidean Figures in Disney’s The Little Mermaid (1989/2008) and Pirates of the Caribbean (2006/2007) -- tReception in Performance: Interview and Poetry -- tAfterword to the Staying Power of Thetis -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex Locorum -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn 1991, Laura Slatkin published The Power of Thetis: Allusion and Interpretation in the Iliad, in which she argued that Homer knowingly situated the storyworld of the Iliad against the backdrop of an older world of mythos by which the events in the Iliad are explained and given traction. Slatkin’s focus was on Achilles’ mother, Thetis: an ostensibly marginal and powerless goddess, Thetis nevertheless drives the plot of the Iliad, being allusively credited with the power to uphold or challenge the rule of Zeus. Now, almost thirty years after Slatkin’s publication, this timely volume re-examines depictions and receptions of this ambiguous goddess, in works ranging from archaic Greek poetry to twenty-first century cinema. Twenty authors build upon Slatkin’s readings to explore Thetis and multiple roles she played in Western literature, art, material culture, religion, and myth. Ever the shapeshifter, Thetis has been and continues to be reconceptualised: supporter or opponent of Zeus’ regime, model bride or unwilling victim of Peleus’ rape, good mother or child-murderess, figure of comedy or monstrous witch. Hers is an enduring power of transformation, resonating within art and literature.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aMythology, Greek, in literature. 4aAntike. 4aMythologie. 4aRezeption. 4aThetis. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aClassical reception.  aGreek mythology.  aThetis.1 aAbad Del Vecchio, Julene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrown, Amelia R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurton, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCannavale, Serena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCingano, Ettore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGuzman, Bettina Joy de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeslin, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJonge, Nile de, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKonstantinou, Ariadne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMartorana, Simona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMassetti, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMawford, Katharine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMilo, Daniela, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaprocki, Maciej, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPaprocki, Maciej, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aScheijnen, Tine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSilverblank, Hannah, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSlatkin, Laura M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relat